Data

The data comes from the UCI machine learning repository. We will work through a regression problem, specifically one interested in predicted the compressive strength of concrete based on multiple factors. Please see the following link which discusses the variables in more detail, as well as the citations about the data.

The code chunk below downloads the Excel file which stores the data and reads it into R. For simplicity, the data set is downloaded into our current working directory.

uci_url <- "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive/Concrete_Data.xls"

download.file(uci_url, destfile = "concrete_data.xls", mode = "wb")

concrete <- readxl::read_xls("concrete_data.xls", col_names = TRUE)

Resampling scheme

We will us k-fold cross-validation to assess overfitting and/or underfitting of the various models we will build. As discussed in lecture, this will help identify if a model is too complex and is thus only explaining the noise in the training data set. K-fold cross-validation is a resampling technique that breaks up the data set into multiple training and test splits. In this demonstration, we will use the caret package to manage the resampling scheme, model training, predictions, and calculation of the performance metrics.

Specifically, we will use 5-fold cross-validation repeated 3 times. In caret, the resampling scheme is specified by the trainControl() function where we specify the method, the number of folds, and if we will repeat the process. In addition to the resampling scheme we must also tell caret what our primary performance metric is. Multiple performance metrics can still be studied, but we will specify the primary metric as the RMSE. The code chunk below defines the variables my_ctrl and my_metric which store the resampling control information and the metric type, respectively.

my_ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 3)

my_metric <- "RMSE"

Model training

We will try out multiple candidate models, ranging from simple to complex. We will start out with linear methods, before trying out non-linear models. The models are trained in caret with the train() function. After specifying the inputs and outputs, and the data, we must tell caret the type of model or the method to use. There are hundreds of models available for training through caret. We will show a handful of those in this demonstration.

The train() function allows us to specify if pre-processing steps are to be applied to the inputs via the preProc argument. caret has a variety of pre-processing actions it can perform, and the nice aspect of including them within the train() directly is that the pre-processing actions are performed on a per-fold basis. Thus, if we center the inputs by subtracting out the mean, the centering is based on the sample average within each fold.

The following code chunks show how to specify other arguments to train(). We will discuss those arguments throughout the semester.

When we train each model we must specify the random seet with the set.seed() function before each train() call. This forces the random data splits within the folds to be same across the models. If we didnât do this, we would not have an apples-to-apples comparison in the cross-validation performance metrics since the hold-out sets would be different between models.

Linear models

Letâs start out with a simple linear model, assuming linear additive terms for all 8 inputs. We can specify the model formulation through the formula interface. Rather than writing out each input to create out simple model, we can use the R short cut . to represent âeverything elseâ. Thus, to tell caret to fit a model for strength as a function of inputs we can write strength ~ .. Note that to use the âeverything elseâ syntax for the inputs, the data set we specify as the data argument to train(), must ONLY contain the inputs and the response. It cannot include other variables, such as observation indices or other variables.

Since the inputs span different ranges, we will standardize the inputs so that all are mean zero and variance one. Thus, our linear model will study the relative effect of each input on the response. To standardize we must instruct caret to first "center" and then "scale" the variables. The code chunk below shows the specific syntax for doing so.

set.seed(20201)
fit_lm <- train(strength ~ ., data = my_concrete,
                method = "lm",
                metric = my_metric,
                preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                trControl = my_ctrl)

Printing the fit_lm result to screen displays useful information which summarizes how the cross-validation, pre-processing, and model training were performed. This way if we ever forget how we trained a model (for example if we saved it for use later on), we can just print the object to screen to tell us that kind of information. The object also tells how how the model performed on average across the hold-out sets.

fit_lm

The simple linear additive regression model is a nice starting point, but obviously itâs limited. Letâs slowly start to increase the complexity by considering interaction terms. In R we can use a shortcut syntax to specify all pair-wise interactions with the formula interface strength ~ (.)^2. At first this seems like we wanted to square âeverything elseâ. However, in R this is a shortcut statement for all pair-wise interactions. If we allow for all pair-wise interactions, the number of unknown coefficients or parameters in our model will increase. We can check just how many coefficients will exist in the model by checking the design matrix. Itâs ok if youâre not sure what the next code chunk represents, we will cover design matrices in detailed in a few lectures. Just look how many parameters we now have to consider compared with the original number of parameters in our simple linear additive model.

model.matrix(strength ~ (.)^2, data = my_concrete) %>% dim()
## [1] 1030   37

Because we have so many more terms when we include interactions, letâs use a penalized or regularized regression model. Regularization tries to prevent large parameter values from occuring. We will use the elastic net model which is a blending of lasso and ridge regression. The elastic net model is contained within the glmnet package and so when you train elastic net the first time with caret, you will be prompted to download the glmnet package. Please follow the onscreen prompts to do so.

The code chunk below trains the elastic net model with all pair-wise interactions, using syntax similar to that of the simple linear additive model. The important changes are though the change in the formula, and the change in the method argument to "glmnet". After training is complete, the caret model object is printed to the screen. Notice how there are multiple rows of performance results. That is because elastic net model consists of two tuning parameters, alpha and lambda. We will talk about these parameters in more detail later in the semester. The important thing to know for now is that more complex models may have parameters that are difficult to learn or fit from the training data directly. Such tuning parameters are optimized via cross-validation.

set.seed(20201)
fit_glmnet_pairs <- train(strength ~ (.)^2, data = my_concrete,
                          method = "glmnet",
                          metric = my_metric,
                          preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                          trControl = my_ctrl)

Letâs consider a linear model that is particularly well suited to deal with correlated inputs. Although we saw the inputs were not highly related to each other in this example, itâs still a useful model to know about. Partial Least Squares (PLS) finds a linear combination of the inputs, and fits those transformed variables to the response. We will apply the linear combinations to all pair-wise interactions rather than the inputs directly. As with elastic-net there is a tuning parameter to optimize for, the number of âlatent componentâ ncomp. The code chunk below shows how to train a PLS model, as well as specify a custom grid search for the tuning parameter. Custom grid searches can provide more fine grain detail when optimizing the tuning parameters.

pls_grid <- expand.grid(ncomp = seq(1, 25, by = 2))

set.seed(20201)
fit_pls <- train(strength ~ (.)^2, data = my_concrete,
                 method = "pls",
                 metric = my_metric,
                 tuneGrid = pls_grid,
                 preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                 trControl = my_ctrl)

Non-linear models

Now letâs try out some more complex models capable of learning non-linear patterns in the data. We will talk these models in more detail later in the semester. We will use a support vector machine (SVM) with a radial basis function, a single layer neural network, a single layer neural network applied to latent variables determined through Principal Components Analysis (PCA), a classification and regression tree (CART), and a random forest model. Each of these models have their own set of tuning parameters. We will discuss how to interpret what these tuning parameters mean later in the course.

Use the default tuning parameter grid search for the SVM model.

set.seed(20201)
fit_svm <- train(strength ~ ., data = my_concrete,
                 method = "svmRadial",
                 metric = my_metric,
                 preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                 trControl = my_ctrl)

Compare models

Now that we have fit all of the models, letâs compare the cross-validation hold-out set performance metrics. We first compile all of the âresampleâ results together with the resamples() function.

my_results <- resamples(list(LM = fit_lm,
                             GLMNET_pairs = fit_glmnet_pairs,
                             GLMNET_trips = fit_glmnet_trips,
                             PLS_pairs = fit_pls,
                             SVM = fit_svm,
                             CART = fit_cart,
                             NNET = fit_nnet_b,
                             NNET_pca = fit_pca_nnet,
                             RF = fit_rf))

Now we can visually compare the performance metrics graphically use a default plotting method.

dotplot(my_results)

Or we can manually extract the results to make a custom figure with ggplot2. Which model seems to be the best?

resamples_lf <- as.data.frame(my_results, metric = "RMSE") %>% tbl_df() %>% 
  mutate(metric_name = "RMSE") %>% 
  bind_rows(as.data.frame(my_results, metric = "Rsquared") %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              mutate(metric_name = "Rsquared")) %>% 
  bind_rows(as.data.frame(my_results, metric = "MAE") %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              mutate(metric_name = "MAE")) %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = "model_name", value = "metric_value", 
                -Resample, -metric_name)

resamples_lf %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = model_name, y = metric_value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_se",
               color = "red",
               fun.args = list(mult = 1)) +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_grid(. ~ metric_name, scales = "free_x") +
  theme_bw()

Hold-out set predictions

By default, caret does not store all of the cross-validation fold hold-out set predictions in order to save memory. Letâs retrain the random forest model and the elastic net with all pair-wise interactions, but this time force all hold-out set predictions to be saved. To do so, the trainControl() function is modified, as shown below.

my_ctrl_pred <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 3,
                             savePredictions = TRUE)

Now retrain the random forest and elastic net models.

set.seed(20201)
fit_rf_pred <- train(strength ~ ., data = my_concrete,
                     method = "rf",
                     metric = my_metric,
                     preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                     trControl = my_ctrl_pred)
set.seed(20201)
fit_glmnet_pairs_pred <- train(strength ~ (.)^2, data = my_concrete,
                               method = "glmnet",
                               metric = my_metric,
                               preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                               trControl = my_ctrl_pred)

Letâs now visualize the random forest hold-out set predictions compared to the observations in a predicted vs observed style figure. The figure below breaks up each fold within each repeat. Visually, how do you think the model performed?

fit_rf_pred$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
  filter(mtry == fit_rf_pred$bestTune$mtry) %>% 
  tidyr::separate(Resample,
                  c("fold_id", "rep_id"),
                  sep = "\\.",
                  remove = FALSE) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = obs, y = pred)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0,
              color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  facet_grid(rep_id ~ fold_id, labeller = "label_both") +
  theme_bw()

Constrast the random forest performance with the elastic net performance.

fit_glmnet_pairs_pred$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
  filter(alpha == fit_glmnet_pairs_pred$bestTune$alpha,
         lambda == fit_glmnet_pairs_pred$bestTune$lambda) %>%

                  c("fold_id", "rep_id"),

Variable importance rankings

Complex non-linear models can be difficult to interpret. After all, they do not consist of simple coefficients that we can compare relative to zero. However, some complex models have methods that can rank the inputs. We will discuss how the random forest model is capable of doing so later in the semester. The variable importance ranking is graphically shown below.

plot(varImp(fit_rf))
